Adding promise is really easy. Just return promise wrapper around itself when the function executed without callback. (but this way can't refer to the Glob instance returns by the function)

```js
function glob (pattern, options, cb) {
  if (typeof options === 'function') cb = options, options = {}
  if (!options) options = {}

  if (options.sync) {
    if (cb)
      throw new TypeError('callback provided to sync glob')
    return globSync(pattern, options)
  }

  // added block <<
  if (!cb) return new Promise(function (resolve, reject) {
    glob(pattern, options, function (er, files) {
      if (er) reject(er)
      else resolve(files)
    })
  })
  // >>

  return new Glob(pattern, options, cb)
}
```

Now Promise is supported by [many versions](https://node.green/#ES2015-built-ins-Promise) and used many to avoid the callback hell.
It is good to let the user promisify, but I think the library itself supports the promise will increase the value of the library.
